nce 2003. He is a member of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]].  The district, numbered as the 7th District from 2003 to 2013, includes the western third of [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], part of [[Yuma, Arizona|Yuma]] and [[Nogales, Arizona|Nogales]], and some peripheral parts of metro [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]].\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nRa\u00fal Grijalva's father was a migrant worker from Mexico who entered the United States in 1945 through the [[Bracero Program]] and labored on southern Arizona ranches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=87&sectiontree=2,87 |title=Congressman Raul M. Grijalva: Biography |publisher=Grijalva.house.gov |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> Grijalva was born in [[Tucson, Arizona]], and graduated from [[Sunnyside High School (Tucson, Arizona)|Sunnyside High School]] in 1967. He is a 2004 inductee to the Sunnyside High School Alumni Hall of Fame. He attended the [[University of Arizona]] and earned a bachelor's degree in [[sociology]]. While at the University, he was a member of [[MEChA|Movimiento Estudiantil Chicano de Aztl\u00e1n (MEChA)]] which, at that time, was a radical group identified with the separatist [[Aztl\u00e1n#Use by the Chicano movement|\"Aztl\u00e1n\"]] ideology. Grijalva also served as a leader of the Chicano Liberation Committee and other Chicano groups.\n\nIn addition, he was an Arizona leader of the [[Raza Unida Party]].  According to the standard history of the party by Dr. Armando Navarro, \"Grijalva was so militant that he alienated some members of Tucson's Mexican-American community. After losing in his first bid for elective office, a 1972 run for a seat on the school board, he began to cultivate a less radical image.\"<ref name=\"www.cis.org\">{{Cite web  | last =  Kammer| first =  Jerry| title = Raul Grijalva: From Chicano Radical to Congressman | publisher =Center for Immigration Studies | url = http://www.cis.org/grijalva | date = October 2009 | accessdate = July 31, 2012 }}</ref><ref>Armando Navarro, La Raza Unida Party, Philadelphia: Temple University Press, 2000, pp. 204.</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he was elected to the [[Tucson Unified School District]] board and served as a school board member until 1986. [[Grijalva Elementary School]] in Tucson was named for him in 1987.<ref>[http://www.tusd.k12.az.us/CONTENTS/schools/detail.asp?searchby=school&searchfield=Grijalva%20Elementary%20School Grijalva Elementary School in TUSD]</ref> From 1975 to 1986, Grijalva was the director of the El Pueblo Neighborhood Center, and in 1987 he was Assistant Dean for Hispanic Student Affairs at the [[University of Arizona]]. Grijalva was a member of the [[Pima County, Arizona|Pima County]] Board of Supervisors from 1989 to 2002, and served as chairman from 2000 to 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grijalva.house.gov/uploads/New%20Curriculum%20Vitae.pdf |title=Rep. Raul M. Grijalva Curriculum Vitae |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Arizona 3rd Congressional District.png|thumb|{{ushr|AZ|3}}, which Grijalva has represented since 2013.]]\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]''' (Ranking Member)\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands|Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n\n===Caucuses===\nGrijalva is a member of several dozen caucuses. A full list is available at his Web site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=44&sectiontree=2,44 |title=Caucus and Task Force Membership |publisher=Grijalva.house.gov |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]] (Co-Chair)\n* [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]] (1st Vice Chair)<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalhispaniccaucus-lujangrisham.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Hispanic Caucus|date=|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n* [[LGBT Equality Caucus]] (Vice Chair)\n* [[Congressional National Landscape Conservation System]] (Co-Chair)\n* [[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]] (Associate Member)<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Justice Democrats#Justice Democrats Caucus|Justice Democrats Caucus]]\n* [[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nGrijalva co-chairs the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]] with [[Mark Pocan]] of Wisconsin<ref>{{cite web|author=Rep Grijalva's official website|title=Congressional Progressive Caucus Members|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/caucus-members|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> and in 2008 was among 12 members rated by ''National Journal'' as tied for most [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] overall.<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/cs_20090228_9659.php National Journal Rankings 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303032717/http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/cs_20090228_9659.php |date=March 3, 2009 }}. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> On the ideological map of all House members at GovTrack's website, Grijalva is ranked farthest to the [[American Left|left]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/raul_grijalva/400162|title=Ra\u00fal Grijalva, Representative for Arizona's 3rd Congressional District - GovTrack.us|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>  Liberal and progressive activist groups routinely give him high marks for his voting record. Grijalva received a 100 percent score from [[Americans for Democratic Action]], [[Peace Action]], the [[League of Conservation Voters]], the [[Leadership Conference on Civil Rights|Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights]], NARAL Pro-Choice America, Arab American Institute,  and several other notable groups in recent years.<ref>[http://grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=94&sectiontree=2,94 Rep. Raul M. Grijalva: Organization Ratings & Scores]. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> With the start of the 114th Congress, Grijalva became the Ranking Member of the House Committee on Natural Resources.\n\nGrijalva is an advocate of [[General Mining Act of 1872|mining law reform]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broncocreek.com/uploads/Rosemont_No.pdf|title=Rosemont No. 1 holder of Pima mining claims|publisher=www.broncocreek.com|date=January 13, 2008|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> and many other environmental causes. From his position on the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|House Committee on Natural Resources]]\u2014where he has been the top Democrat on the [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands|Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands]] since 2007\u2014he has led Democratic efforts to strengthen federal offshore oil drilling oversight since before the 2010 [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/e2-wire/677-e2-wire/130345-house-dems-press-interior-to-finish-probe-of-bp-atlantis-operation|title=Fearing second Gulf spill, House Dems press Interior to finish probe of platform|publisher=The Hill|date=November 23, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> and introduced a successful bill to create a permanent [[National Landscape Conservation System]] at the Bureau of Land Management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=487770&keyword=&phrase=&contain=|title=Partial speech transcript on Omnibus Public Land Management Act Of 2009|publisher=Project VoteSmart|date=March 11, 2009|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> He was a leading candidate for [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] when President Obama was elected, but the job eventually went to [[Ken Salazar]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2008/11/21/grijalva_in_running_for_interi.html |title=Grijalva In the Running |publisher=Voices.washingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\u2014according to the ''Washington Post'', President Obama made the decision in part because of Grijalva's stated preference for more environmental analysis before approving offshore drilling projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/12/AR2010101206279.html|title=Lifting the drilling moratorium: How politics spilled into policy|publisher=Washington Post|date=October 13, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011|first1=Michael|last1=Leahy|first2=Juliet|last2=Eilperin}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a vocal opponent of [[Arizona immigration law (2010)|Arizona's SB 1070 law]] that mandates police checks of citizenship documentation for anyone subjected to a legitimate law enforcement stop, detention or arrest as long as the officer does not consider race, color or national origin during the stop, detention or arrest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azleg.gov/FormatDocument.asp?inDoc=/legtext/49leg/2r/laws/0211.htm |title=Arizona House Bill 2162 - Filled by the Secretary of State 30 April 2010 |publisher=Azleg.gov |date=April 30, 2010 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> Shortly after the measure was signed by Arizona Governor [[Jan Brewer]], Grijalva called on legal, political, activist and business groups not to hold their conventions or conferences in the state, a position that he said quickly became misconstrued as a call for a general boycott of the state economy.<ref>[http://www.kgun9.com/Global/story.asp?S=12370522 Grijalva calls for economic boycott]. Retrieved June 2, 2010.</ref> In response, the Arizona Republican Party handed out bumper stickers reading \"Boycott Grijalva, Not Arizona.\"  After a federal judge stopped implementation of most of SB 1070, Grijalva withdrew the boycott, saying that he had reacted to it \"very personally.\"  In an interview regarding the situation, Grijalva said that \"to all of a sudden have a law that separates me from the whole, I found very offensive and demeaning.\"  <ref>{{cite news|author=Riccardi, Nicholas|title=In Arizona, a candidate faces a boycott backlash|date=October 23, 2010|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/23/nation/la-na-grijalva-campaign-20101023|work=LA Times|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe criticized the 2010 deployment of 1,200 [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops to the [[Mexico \u2013 United States border|U.S.-Mexico border]] as \"political symbolism\" that he believed would not adequately address the issues of immigration and border security.<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/2010/5/28/arizona New Deployment of National Guard to US-Mexico Border Is Election-Year \"Political Symbolism\"]. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref>\n\nGrijalva has frequently called for a withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan and Iraq, and supports the wider implementation of the [[Afghan National Solidarity Programme|National Solidarity Program]] as a way to improve Afghans' economic and educational infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslaboragainstwar.org/article/article.php?id=19354 |title=US Labor Against the War : Congressional Progressive Afghanistan/Pakistan Forum: Preliminary Summary |publisher=Uslaboragainstwar.org |date=May 13, 2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> The group [[Iraq and Afghanistan Veterans of America]] gave him an \"A\" rating for the 2007-2008 Congressional session.\n\n===Abortion===\nGrijalva has a [[pro-choice]] voting record and voted against the [[Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ontheissues.org/House/Raul_Grijalva_Abortion.htm |title=Raul Grijalva on Abortion |publisher=Ontheissues.org |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> He was strongly critical of the [[Stupak-Pitts Amendment]], which sought to place limits on taxpayer-funded abortions in the [[Affordable Health Care for America Act]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Slajda |url=http://tpmlivewire.talkingpointsmemo.com/2009/11/grijalva-vows-to-fight-trigger-opt-out-stupak-amendment.php |title=Grijalva Vows To Fight Trigger, Opt-Out, Stupak Amendment |publisher=Tpmlivewire.talkingpointsmemo.com |date=November 10, 2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Budget proposals===\nAs co-chair of the Congressional Progressive Caucus, Rep. Grijalva has taken a leading role in shaping recent CPC \"alternative budgets\"\u2014budget bills offered by various groups and caucuses in Congress other than the official majority or minority party plan. In 2011 the CPC introduced what it called the People's Budget, which reached budget balance in 10 years according to an assessment by the [[Economic Policy Institute]] based on nonpartisan government data.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew |last=Fieldhouse |url=http://www.epi.org/publication/the_peoples_budget_a_technical_analysis/ | title=The People's Budget: A Technical Analysis | publisher=Economic Policy Institute |date=April 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> The proposal was noted approvingly by some of the world's leading economists, including [[Jeffrey Sachs]]\u2014who called it \"a bolt of hope . . . humane, responsible, and most of all sensible\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Jeffrey |last=Sachs |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeffrey-sachs/the-peoples-budget_b_846573.html |title=The People's Budget |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=April 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref>\u2014and [[Paul Krugman]], who called it \"genuinely courageous\" for achieving budget balance \"without dismantling the legacy of the New Deal.\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Krugman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/25/opinion/25krugman.html?_r=1&ref=opinion | title=Let's Take a Hike | publisher=The New York Times |date=April 25, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Budget of the Congressional Progressive Caucus Fiscal Year 2012|url=http://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=70|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, again with Grijalva as co-chair, the Progressive Caucus introduced the Budget for All, which is similar to the People's Budget and includes several new features, including a novel proposal to institute a small personal wealth tax above $10 million in net worth phased in over a period of five years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nichols|first=John|title=A Budget For Wall Street Versus A Budget For Main Street|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/167084/budget-wall-street-versus-budget-main-street|newspaper=The Nation|date=March 28, 2012}}</ref> The proposal received 78 votes, all from Democrats, when the House considered it on March 29, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Budget of the Congressional Progressive Caucus Fical Year 2013 |url=http://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=81&sectiontree=5,81 |publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723123441/http://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=81&sectiontree=5,81 |archivedate=July 23, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Henry|first=Devin|title=House votes down Progressive Caucus budget|url=http://www.minnpost.com/dc-dispatches/2012/03/house-votes-down-progressive-caucus-budget|newspaper=MinnPost|date=March 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Deepwater Horizon and oil rig safety===\nOn Feb 24, 2010, Grijalva wrote a letter signed by 18 other Representatives calling for an investigation of the [[BP Atlantis]] [[offshore drilling]] platform due to whistleblower allegations that it was operating without approved safety documents.<ref>[http://blogs.chron.com/newswatchenergy/archives/2010/05/lawmakers_seek.html Lawmakers seek halt to production at BP's Atlantis platform]. Retrieved June 2, 2010.</ref> He has called for Atlantis to be shut down.<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/37232206 Lawmakers to urge BP to idle its Atlantis rig]. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> Since the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]] on April 20, 2010, Grijalva has written letters to the Minerals Management Service and the Department of the Interior questioning current offshore drilling regulations and calling for stronger oversight of the oil industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=107&sectiontree=4,107 |title=Rep. Raul M. Grijalva: Official Letters and Oversight |publisher=Grijalva.house.gov |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nGrijalva has gained prominence as an outspoken critic of what he calls lax federal oversight of the oil drilling industry, and in late 2010 launched an investigation of the White House's handling of the Horizon spill and its aftermath. That investigation revealed that scientists at the Environmental Protection Agency and elsewhere in the federal government had voiced concerns about drafts of an official government report on the cause and scope of the spill, but were overruled because the report was meant as a \"communications document\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/01/25/grijalva-white-house-oil-spill-report-spin_n_813933.html|title=Congressman Accuses White House Of Putting Spin Above Science|publisher=Huffington Post|date=January 25, 2011|accessdate=March 22, 2011|first=Dan|last=Froomkin}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he introduced H.R. 5355 to eliminate the cap on oil company liability for the cost of environmental cleanups of spills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2010/5/28/bp_oil_spill_confirmed_as_worst|title=BP Oil Spill Confirmed as Worst in US History; Environmental Groups Challenge Continued Oil Operations in Gulf Excluded from New Moratorium|publisher=Democracy Now|date=May 28, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nGrijalva has sponsored numerous education bills during his time in Congress, including the Success in the Middle Act<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmsa.org/Advocacy/MessagesfromNMSA/SuccessintheMiddleAct/tabid/1482/Default.aspx |title=Success in the Middle Act |publisher=Nmsa.org |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> and the Graduation for All Act.<ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h111-4122 Education for All Act] GovTrack</ref> Grijalva has long ties to the educational community from his time on the board of the Tucson Unified School District and his current position on the House Education and the Workforce Committee.\n\n===Environment===\nAs a member and chairman of the [[Pima County, Arizona|Pima County]] Board of Supervisors, Grijalva was widely regarded as a central figure behind the Sonoran Desert Conservation Plan,<ref>{{cite web|last=Herreras |first=Mari |url=http://www.tucsonweekly.com/gbase/Currents/Content?oid=42757 |title=Currents : Beating Ra\u00fal |publisher=Tucson Weekly |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> an ambitious County program for planned land-use and biodiversity conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pima.gov/CMO/SDCP/ |title=Sonoran Desert Conservation Plan |publisher=Pima.gov |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> He consistently supported endangered species and wilderness conservation on the Board of Supervisors and has continued to do so in Congress, introducing a bill in 2009 to make permanent the [[National Landscape Conservation System]] within the [[Bureau of Land Management]]. In 2008, Grijalva released a report called ''The Bush Administration's Assaults on Our National Parks, Forests and Public Lands,''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://grijalva.house.gov/uploads/Grijalva_Public_Lands_Report_10_22_20081.pdf | title = A REPORT on THE BUSH ADMINISTRATION ASSAULTS ON OUR NATIONAL PARKS, FORESTS AND PUBLIC LANDS | accessdate = October 29, 2010 | last = Grijalva | first = Ra\u00fal M. | date = October 22, 2008 | publisher = Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands United States House of Representatives}}</ref> which accused the Bush administration of mismanaging public land and reducing barriers to commercial access.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nationalparkstraveler.com/2008/10/bush-administration-legacy-failure-our-public-lands-claims-congressman-grijalva | title = Updated: Bush Administration: \"A Legacy of Failure for Our Public Lands,\" Claims Congressman Grijalva | accessdate = October 29, 2010 | last = Repanshek | first = Kurt | date = October 30, 2008 | work = National Parks Traveler | publisher = National Park Advocates LLC}}</ref>\n\nThe Trump administration proposed changes to \"the way it enforces the [[Endangered Species Act]]\" in 2018. Among other things, the proposal would facilitate delising endangered species and \"streamline interagency consultations\". Grijalva, a ranking member of the [[House Natural Resources Committee]] at the time, referred to the proposal as \"a favor to industry\". He posited that the administration \"doesn\u2019t seem to know any other way to handle the environment\" than \"as an obstacle to industry profits\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=GREEN |first1=MIRANDA |last2=Cama |first2=TIMOTHY |title=Trump administration introduces proposal to roll back Endangered Species Act protections |url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/397905-trump-administration-introduce-proposal-to-roll-back-endangered |website=The Hill |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nIn 2011, Grijalva along with Democratic Representatives [[Barbara Lee]], [[Mike Honda]], and [[Lynn Woolsey]] criticized Obama for failing to seek congressional authorization for [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]],<ref>https://www.politico.com/story/2011/03/liberal-dems-disengage-in-libya-051766</ref> and were one of the 70 Democrats to vote to defund the Libyan war.<ref>https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/06/24/despite-vote-majority-of-congressmen-want-to-defund-the-libya-war/</ref> In 2013, Grijalva opposed intervening in Syria.<ref>http://inthesetimes.com/article/15558/the_strange_majority_against_syrian_intervention</ref>\n\n===Fossil fuel industry funding of climate change studies===\nOn February 24, 2015, as the ranking Democratic member of the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources]], Grijalva sent letters to seven institutions employing scientists who disagree with most other climate scientists on man-made climate change. The letters requested information on any funding from [[fossil fuel]] companies, as well as copies of all emails concerning the content of their congressional testimony. One of the recipients, University of Colorado Professor [[Roger Pielke Jr.]], responded that he had already testified to Grijalva's committee that he has received no funding from fossil fuel interests, and characterized the letter as part of a politically motivated \"'witch-hunt'\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dickie|first1=Gloria|title=CU-Boulder's Roger Pielke Jr. targeted by congressman over research funding|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/cu-news/ci_27593340/cu-boulders-roger-pielke-jr-says-congressman-is|accessdate=3 March 2015|work=(Boulder, CO) Daily Camera|date=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe heads of some mainstream scientific organizations criticized Grijalva's letters. [[Margaret Leinen]], the president of the [[American Geophysical Union]] posted in her AGU blog that in requiring information only of only a few scientists, based only on their scientific views, Grivalja's action was contrary to academic freedom: \"We view the singling out of any individual or group of scientists by any entity \u2013 governmental, corporate or other \u2013 based solely on their interpretations of scientific research as a threat to that freedom.\"<ref>Margaret Leinen, [http://fromtheprow.agu.org/blog/protecting-academic-freedom-holding-accountable/ Protectinng academic freedom], 27 February 2015.</ref> The executive director of the [[American Meteorological Society]] wrote in a letter to Grvalja that his action \"sends a chilling message to all academic researchers,\" and \"impinges on the free pursuit of ideas that is central to the concept of academic freedom.\"<ref>Dr. Keith L. Seitter,  [http://www.ametsoc.org/sss/letter_on_challenges_to_academic_freedom_Feb15.pdf Letter on challenges to academic freedom], 27 Feb. 2015.</ref>\n\nIn response to criticism that requesting communications was counter to principles of [[academic freedom]], Grijalva said he was willing to eliminate that part of the request.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Geman|first1=Ben|title=Grijalva: Climate Letters Went Too Far in Seeking Correspondence|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/energy/grijalva-climate-letters-went-too-far-in-seeking-correspondence-20150302|accessdate=3 March 2015|work=National Journal|date=2 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\nGrijalva supports increasing restrictions on the purchase and possession of guns and increasing enforcement of existing restrictions on gun purchase and possession.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/npat.php?can_id=28253#11426 Gun Issues] from ''Project Vote Smart''</ref> He was one of the 67 co-sponsors of the [[Assault Weapons Ban and Law Enforcement Protection Act of 2007|2007 Assault Weapons Ban, HR 1022]].<ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d110:HR01022:@@@P H.R.1022] ''THOMAS (Library of Congress)''</ref>  Grijalva has an F rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_detail.php?r_id=4229 |title=National Special Interest Groups |publisher=Project Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Health care ===\nAs co-chair of the Progressive Caucus, Grijalva was a prominent supporter of a public option throughout the debate over the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1109/29079.html Strong public option a cure for system]. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> The House-approved [[Affordable Health Care for America Act]] included a public option \u2014 however, the Senate version did not include a similar provision, and it was ultimately not a part of the final reform package. Grijalva has largely been supportive of the health care reform law since its passage and argued the Supreme Court should not overturn it during a segment with Republican Rep. [[Peter Roskam]], who opposes the law, for the [[PBS NewsHour]] on March 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/health/jan-june12/house-members_03-28.html |title=Congressmen on Political, Practical Stakes of Court's Health Reform Ruling |publisher=PBS NewsHour |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGrijalva has a long history in community health activism as an early supporter of Tucson's El Rio Community Health Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=87&sectiontree=2,87 |title=Rep. Raul M. Grijalva Biography |publisher=Grijalva.house.gov |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> He supports single-payer health care, but voted in favor of the Patient Protection and Affordable Health Care Act because he felt it was a major improvement over the status quo.<ref>{{YouTube|IY8us7FZfbg|Rep. Grijalva on Arizona Illustrated April 1}}. Retrieved June 2, 2010.</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nGrijalva supports the [[DREAM Act]] and the Comprehensive Immigration Reform for America's Security and Prosperity Act (CIR ASAP) and has recently come to greater prominence because of his role in promoting immigration reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperialvalleynews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6806&Itemid=2 |title=Grijalva Supports Comprehensive House Immigration Reform Effort, Hails Economic Benefits |publisher=Imperialvalleynews.com |date=December 15, 2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://thehill.com/homenews/house/95509-arizona-law-controversy-raises-grijalvas-profile-along-with-immigration-issue Arizona Law Controversy Raises Grijalva's Profile Along With Immigration Issue]. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> He has opposed the expansion of a border fence, citing cost effectiveness concerns and potential damage to sensitive wildlife habitats.<ref>[http://www.grist.org/article/hurowitz Why environmental groups have been slow to fight the border wall]. Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> The CIR ASAP bill includes his Border Security and Responsibility Act of 2009, which prioritizes remote cameras and other border monitoring techniques with a relatively slight environmental impact. The Immigrant Justice Advocacy Campaign gave him a 100 percent score for the first session of the 111th Congress. In previous years he voted against [[H.R. 4437]] and [[Secure Fence Act of 2006|the Secure Fence Act]], and opposed [[Arizona Proposition 200 (2004)|Arizona Proposition 200]] in 2004.\n\nGrijalva has criticized armed civilian groups that patrol the Mexican border, accusing them of being \"racist\" and has reportedly used demeaning language to describe them.  In return, some supporters of the armed patrols have called him \"MEChA boy\" in retaliation.<ref name=\"www.cis.org\"/><ref name=\"TucsonCitizen\">{{Cite web  | last =  | first =  | title = Callers split on border crossers, civilian patrols: TUCSON CITIZEN MORGUE, PART 2 (1993-2009) | url = http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2003/01/27/35965-callers-split-on-border-crossers-civilian-patrols/ | publisher = Tucson Citizen | date = January 27, 2003 | accessdate = July 31, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Native Americans ===\nGrijalva is a strong supporter of sovereignty and government-to-government relationships. In April 2010 he introduced the RESPECT Act, which mandates that federal agencies consult with Native tribes before taking a variety of major actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opencongress.org/bill/111-h5023/show |title=H.R.5023: Requirements, Expectations, and Standard Procedures for Executive Consultation with Tribes Act - U.S OpenCongress |publisher=Opencongress.org |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> The bill would codify a Clinton-era executive order that has never had the force of law.\n\n=== SB 1070 and the boycott controversy ===\nAfter the passage in April 2010 of [[Arizona immigration law (2010)|Arizona's controversial SB 1070 law]], which he saw as opening the door to racial profiling and granting traditionally federal immigration enforcement powers to local authorities,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/nov/04/news/la-pn-grijalva-20101104|title=Rep. Raul Grijalva's win in Arizona gives liberals something to cheer|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=November 4, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011|first=Nicholas|last=Riccardi}}</ref> Grijalva suggested that civic, religious, labor, Latino, and other like-minded organizations refrain from using Arizona as a convention site until the law was repealed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lemons |first=Stephen |url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/bastard/2010/04/post_2.php |title=Raul Grijalva Urges Boycott of Arizona, and Scott Rasmussen Proves That a Majority of Arizonans Are Bigots - Phoenix News - Feathered Bastard |publisher=Blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com |date=April 21, 2010 |accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> His opposition to SB 1070, as well as his suggestion of a boycott of Arizona, was widely viewed as the reason for multiple subsequent death threats against him and his staff, which led to several office closures in the spring of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kvoa.com/news/breaking-news-death-threats-close-grijalvas-offices/|title=BREAKING NEWS: Death threats close Grijalva's offices|publisher=KVOA.com|date=April 23, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Susan Ritchie Bolton|Judge Susan Bolton]] of the Arizona District Court enjoined major parts of the law <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2010/07/28/888428/-SB-1070-Largely-Enjoined:-The-Opinion|title=SB 1070 Largely Enjoined: The Opinion|publisher=Daily Kos|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> in July 2010, Grijalva ended his call for economic sanctions. As he told the ''Arizona Daily Star'', the largest paper in Tucson:\n\n<blockquote>\"After this ruling, everybody has some responsibility to pause, and that includes me,\" said Grijalva, a Tucson Democrat. \"The issue of economic sanctions is a moot point now and I will encourage national organizations I'm in contact with to come and lend a hand - not just economically, but to help us begin to educate people about how we need to fix this broken system.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://azstarnet.com/news/local/border/article_95bf52a5-6875-5453-b323-b9e954fd682b.html|title=Boycotts going forward despite Grijalva's plea|publisher=Arizona Daily Star|date=July 29, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe subsequently said that his economic strategy was not as effective as he hoped in changing other state lawmakers' minds, and that he would focus on legal remedies in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kvoa.com/news/grijalva-explains-boycot-cancellation/|title=Grijalva explains boycott cancellation|publisher=KVOA.com|date=August 3, 2010|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> The issue became a focal point in the 2010 election, in which Grijalva ultimately defeated Republican challenger Ruth McClung by less than 10,000 votes.\n\n=== 2004 voting irregularities ===\nConcerned about allegations of voting irregularities purportedly leading to [[disenfranchisement]], in 2004 Grijalva joined Congresswoman [[Eddie Bernice Johnson]] and several other House Democrats in requesting that the [[United Nations]] observe and certify elections in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=House members will discuss request to United Nations to monitor election\n|url=http://www.house.gov/apps/list/press/tx30_johnson/HouseMembersUnitedNationsElectionMonitor.html\n|work=Congresswoman Eddie Bernice Johnson|accessdate=December 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[United States presidential election, 2004|General Election]], Grijalva was one of 31 Representatives who voted in the House not to count the [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral votes]] from [[Ohio]] on grounds of unacceptable irregularities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2005/roll007.xml |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 7 |publisher=clerk.house.gov |date=January 6, 2005 |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Giffords shooting ===\nAfter the shooting of [[Gabrielle Giffords]], Grijalva called it a consequence of the violent rhetoric that had been used by Tea Party members. Grijalva singled out [[Sarah Palin]]'s rhetoric as \"contributing to this toxic climate\" and stated that she needs to monitor her words and actions.<ref>{{cite news|author=Grim, Ryan|title=Grijalva: Tea Party Must Look At Their Own Behavior|date=January 8, 2011|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/01/08/grijalva-palin-needs-to-l_n_806283.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\nAfter the [[2000 United States Census]], Arizona gained two Congressional districts. The 2nd District, which had long been represented by Democrat [[Mo Udall]], was renumbered as the 7th District. [[Ed Pastor]], a [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] Democrat who had succeeded Udall in 1991, had his home drawn into the newly created 4th District and opted to run for election there, making the 7th District an [[open seat]]. Grijalva won a crowded seven-way Democratic primary, which was [[tantamount to election]] in this heavily Democratic, majority-Hispanic district. Before the 2010 election, he was reelected three times with no substantial [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] opposition. In 2008, he defeated Republican challenger Joseph Sweeney.\n\nDuring the 2008 presidential campaign, Grijalva endorsed [[Barack Obama]] for President; his district, however, was won by [[Hillary Clinton]].\n\nDuring the 2010 midterms, Grijalva faced his toughest re-election campaign yet, against Republican Ruth McClung. It was reported that although Grijalva had decades of experience and McClung had none, and although there were twice as many Democrats in the district as there were Republicans, the two candidates were neck-and-neck in the polls. The main reason was Grijalva's call for a boycott of Arizona in response to the state's new immigration law, SB 1070. Grijalva won 50%-44% -- his closest margin of victory since being elected, and the first close election in what is now the 7th since 1978, when Udall was held to only 52 percent of the vote.\n\nGrijalva's district was renumbered as the 3rd District after the 2010 census, and made somewhat more Democratic than its predecessor even though it lost some of its share of Tucson to the 2nd District (the reconfigured 8th). Co-chair of the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]], Grijalva broke from many of his colleagues and announced his support for Democratic presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] on 9 October 2015 at a rally for Sanders in Tucson, Arizona.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bernie Sanders Gets First Congressional Endorsement, From Ra\u00fal Grijalva|url = https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/10/07/bernie-sanders-gets-first-congressional-endorsement-from-ral-grijalva/|website = The New York Times - First Draft|date = 2015-10-07|accessdate = 2015-10-09|first = Alan|last = Rappeport}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arizona's 7th Congressional District Democratic Primary Election, 2002\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Ra\u00fal M. Grijalva'''\n|14,835\n|40.85\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Elaine Richardson\n|7,589\n|20.89\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Jaime Gutierrez\n|5,401\n|14.87\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Lisa Otondo\n|2,302\n|6.34\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Luis Armando Gonzales\n|2,105\n|5.80\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Mark Fleisher\n|2,022\n|5.57\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Sherry Smith\n|1,058\n|2.91\n|-\n|Democratic\n|J\u00e9sus Romo\n|1,008\n|2.78\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arizona's 3rd Congressional District Democratic Primary Election, 2012\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Ra\u00fal Grijalva*'''\n|24,044\n|65.63\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Amanda Aguirre\n|9,484\n|25.89\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Manny Arreguin\n|3,105\n|8.48\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ {{ushr|Arizona|7|}}: Results 2002\u20132010<ref name=\"clerkresults\">{{cite web |url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |title=Election Statistics |accessdate=January 10, 2008 |publisher=Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives }}; for 2008 see [[United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2008]]</ref> Arizona's 3rd Congressional District Results 2012\n! Year\n!\n! Democratic\n! Votes\n! Pct\n!\n! Republican\n! Votes\n! Pct\n!\n! 3rd Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! Pct\n!\n! 3rd Par